GUV_Analysis_summary

James Foster

2025-12-18

Details

AUTHOR

James Foster \(2025~06~05\)

MODIFIED

James Foster \(2025~12~18\)

DESCRIPTION

Loads the reorganised data from colour_dance_reorg.csv, saved from GUV_organisedata.R, and generates plots to show the how dances changed as a function of light stimulus.

INPUTS

colour_dance_reorg.csv, Edrich1979_brightness-accuracy.csv

OUTPUTS

Plotted results.

CHANGES

REFERENCES

Edrich, W., Neumeyer, C. and von Helversen, O. (1979). Anti-sun orientation of bees with regard to a field of ultraviolet light. J. Comp. Physiol. 134, 151157.

Rossel, S. and Wehner, R. (1984). Celestial orientation in bees: the use of spectral cues. J. Comp. Physiol. A 155, 605613.

TODO

  • move necessary functions to GUV_functions
  • move raw data to end
  • make functions for result extraction from BRMS
  • neaten up priors for BRMS models

Setting up

First load the functions and packages required for this project. These can all be found in GUV_functions.R, within the same Github repository.

source('GUV_functions.R')

Then load the data that will be used. This includes our own dance data, reorganised by GUV_organisedata.R as colour_dance_reorg.csv, as well as data from Edrich et al. (1979) on the relationship between accuracy (mean vector length), wavelength and intensity. This was manually extracted from Fig. 2 and saved in "Edrich1979_brightness-accuracy.csv.

#Dance angle data
cd = read.table(file = '1Data/colour_dance_reorg.csv', 
                header = T, 
                sep  = ',')
#Accuracy data
ed = read.table(file = '1Data/Edrich1979_brightness-accuracy.csv', 
                header = T, 
                sep  = ',')
#Inspect each dataset
print(cd)

cd = within(cd,
            {
              ID = as.factor(ID) # beedance identifier as a factor
              date = as.factor(date) # date as a factor
              signed_angle = Mod360.180(bearing)  # bearing between -180 and 180
              angle = circular(rad(signed_angle),# bearing between -pi and pi
                               rotation = 'clock') # circular format suppresses later warnings
            }
)
u_id = with(cd, unique(ID)) # unique beedances

Non-parametric tests on accuracy

Here non-parametric or parametric statistics could be revealing.

#Identify all effects as factors for aligned ranks transform
mean_vectors_full = within(mean_vectors_full,
                           {
                           colour = as.factor(colour)
                           brightn = as.factor(brightn)
                           ID = as.factor(ID)
                           }
                           )
mean_vectors = within(mean_vectors,
                           {
                           colour = as.factor(colour)
                           brightn = as.factor(brightn)
                           ID = as.factor(ID)
                           }
                           )
mv_full_art = art(formula = mean_vector~colour*brightn +
                              (1+colour+brightn|ID),#insufficient DF to estimate interaction
                   data = mean_vectors_full)
sm_mv_full_art = summary(mv_full_art)
## boundary (singular) fit: see help('isSingular')
## boundary (singular) fit: see help('isSingular')
## boundary (singular) fit: see help('isSingular')
#check if rank alignment was successful
message('\nSuccessful rank alignment:\n',
        all(sapply(sm_mv_full_art[11], round) == 0),
        '\n')
## 
## Successful rank alignment:
## TRUE
print(anova(mv_full_art), digits = 3)

We can successfully fit an aligned ranks model to compare across individuals. Note that the boundary level random effects indicate that individual effects were too small to estimate. In the individual linear models (e.g.summary(artlm(mv_full_art, "brightn"))$varcor) there may still be substantial individual differences. The primary effect appears to be that of brightness, but there may also be effects of interest in the post-hoc contrasts.

cn_mv_full_art = sapply(X = c('brightn', 'colour', 'colour:brightn'),
                        FUN = ART_extract,
                        mod = mv_full_art,
                        adjust = 'sidak')
## NOTE: Results may be misleading due to involvement in interactions

## 
## Degrees-of-freedom method: kenward-roger 
## P value adjustment: sidak method for 6 tests

The post-hoc tests indicate a large difference between bright and dim conditions, as expected, but very little evidence for differences between colours. The interactions (for which there was low support in the overall model) reflect the pattern we expect, that all bright conditions have higher accuracy than all dim conditions, and that while the two dim conditions have similar accuracy, the bright UV bright condition may be slightly more accurate the bright green condition (p = 0.158). ### Parametric beta-distributed model of accuracy To investigate this with greater statistical power we would need an appropriate parametric model for bounded variables. One approach is to use the beta distribution, which is defined between (but not at) 0 and 1.

Beta model for accuracy

#TODO remove unnecessary priors
### Maximal formula with all random effects ---------------------
#set up model formula with indiv effects on light type
frm_bmod_maxRE = bf(mean_vector~brightn*colour + # light types affect accuracy
                            (1 + brightn*colour|ID), # each individual is more or less oriented
              phi ~ brightn*colour + # light types affect variance in accuracy
                      (1 + brightn*colour|ID), # some individuals vary more in accuracy than others
              family = brms::Beta()) 

#suggest prior values
pr_mu_Intercept = list(dist = 'normal',
             mu = 0,
             sd = 1)#deconstrain to beat divergences?
pr_phi_Intercept = list(dist = 'normal',
             mu = 1,
             sd = 1)
pr_mu_b = list(dist = 'normal',
             mu = 0,
             sd = 1)#deconstrain to beat divergences?
pr_phi_b = list(dist = 'normal',
             mu = 0,
             sd = 1)
pr_mu_sd_Intercept = list(dist = 'student_t',
             df = 3,
             mu = 0,
             sd = 0.1)#constrain to beat divergences?
pr_phi_sd_Intercept = list(dist = 'student_t',
                 df = 3,
                 mu = 0,
                 sd = 0.1)#constrain to beat divergences?
pr_mu_sd = list(dist = 'student_t',
             df = 3,
             mu = 0,
             sd = 0.1)#constrain to beat divergences?
pr_phi_sd = list(dist = 'student_t',
                 df = 3,
                 mu = 0,
                 sd = 0.1)#constrain to beat divergences?

### Assign priors --------------------------------------------------------

#set priors on:
# - all coefficients to a normal(0,1) = 95% probability of values 0.120.87
# - all grouping paramters to a student_t(df = 3, mu = 0, sigma = 2.5) = values < 5.88
# - all other parameters (?) to a normal(0,10)= 95% probability of values 01 +- 1e-7

pr_expression = expression({
  prior = sapply(class, 
                 switch,
                 Intercept = with(pr_mu_Intercept,
                          {paste0(dist,'(',mu,',',sd,')')}),
                 #the general prior for coefficients (should centre on 0)
                 b = with(pr_mu_b,
                          {paste0(dist,'(',mu,',',sd,')')}),
                 #the general prior for standard deviations (should be long-tailed)
                 sd =  with(pr_mu_sd,
                           {paste0(dist,'(',df,',',mu,',',sd,')')}),
                 cor = 'lkj(1)', # The only supported prior for correlation matrices is the 'lkj' prior
                 'normal(0,1)' # with this many params need more informative priors
      )
  #special priors
    #mu sd intercept
  prior[dpar %in% '' & class %in% 'sd' & coef %in% ''] =  
    with(pr_mu_sd_Intercept,
                          {paste0(dist,'(',df,',',mu,',',sd,')')})
  #phi b
  prior[dpar %in% 'phi' & class %in% 'b'] =  
    with(pr_phi_b,
                          {paste0(dist,'(',mu,',',sd,')')})
  #phi intercept
  prior[dpar %in% 'phi' & class %in% 'b' & coef %in% ''] =  
    with(pr_phi_Intercept,
                          {paste0(dist,'(',mu,',',sd,')')})
  #phi sd
  prior[dpar %in% 'phi' & class %in% 'sd'] =  
    with(pr_phi_sd,
                          {paste0(dist,'(',df,',',mu,',',sd,')')})  
  #phi sd intercept
  prior[dpar %in% 'phi' & class %in% 'sd' & coef %in% ''] =  
    with(pr_phi_sd_Intercept,
                          {paste0(dist,'(',df,',',mu,',',sd,')')})
}
)

#model with all random effects
priors_bmod_mxRE = within(get_prior(formula = frm_bmod_maxRE, 
                                    data = mean_vectors_full), 
                          expr = eval(pr_expression))
print(priors_bmod_mxRE)#all parameters are accounted for
##               prior     class             coef group resp dpar nlpar lb ub tag
##         normal(0,1)         b                                                 
##         normal(0,1)         b         brightnl                                
##         normal(0,1)         b brightnl:colouru                                
##         normal(0,1)         b          colouru                                
##              lkj(1)       cor                                                 
##              lkj(1)       cor                     ID                          
##         normal(0,1) Intercept                                                 
##  student_t(3,0,0.1)        sd                                         0       
##  student_t(3,0,0.1)        sd                     ID                  0       
##  student_t(3,0,0.1)        sd         brightnl    ID                  0       
##  student_t(3,0,0.1)        sd brightnl:colouru    ID                  0       
##  student_t(3,0,0.1)        sd          colouru    ID                  0       
##  student_t(3,0,0.1)        sd        Intercept    ID                  0       
##         normal(1,1)         b                              phi                
##         normal(0,1)         b         brightnl             phi                
##         normal(0,1)         b brightnl:colouru             phi                
##         normal(0,1)         b          colouru             phi

This seems to suggest that dances were more accurate in the bright UV condition, which the aligned-ranks test was sceptical of. We can quantify this difference by extracting and comparing the parameter estimates from each (post-warmup) iteration of the model.

draws_beta = prepare_predictions(md_beta,
                                 re_formula = NA)#just population level effects
#for the average vector length
draws_mu = draws_beta$dpars$mu$fe$b
#for variance in vector length
draws_phi = draws_beta$dpars$phi$fe$b
#N.B. Could also just calculate predictions, then subtract
contr_mu = with(data.frame(draws_mu),
                {
                  data.frame(
                    #bright green -> dim green = low brightness effect
                    gh_gl = b_brightnl, 
                    #bright UV -> dim UV = dim + UVdim - UV effect
                    uvh_uvl = b_brightnl + `b_brightnl.colouru` - b_colouru, 
                    #bright green -> bright UV = UV effect
                    gh_uvh = b_colouru, 
                    #bright green -> dim UV = UV + dim + UVdim
                    gh_uvl = b_brightnl + b_colouru + `b_brightnl.colouru`, 
                    #dim green -> dim UV = UV effect + UVdim - dim effect
                    gl_uvl = b_colouru + `b_brightnl.colouru` - b_brightnl
                  )
                }
                )
#On the original scale
contr_rho = with(data.frame(draws_mu),
                {
                  data.frame(
                    #bright green -> dim green = low brightness effect
                    gh_gl = plogis(b_Intercept + b_brightnl) -
                              plogis(b_Intercept), 
                    #bright UV -> dim UV = dim + UVdim - UV effect
                    uvh_uvl = plogis(b_Intercept + b_brightnl + `b_brightnl.colouru`) - 
                              plogis(b_Intercept + b_colouru), 
                    #bright green -> bright UV = UV effect
                    gh_uvh = plogis(b_Intercept + b_colouru) -
                              plogis(b_Intercept), 
                    #bright green -> dim UV = UV + dim + UVdim
                    gh_uvl = plogis(b_Intercept + b_brightnl + 
                                      b_colouru + `b_brightnl.colouru`)- 
                              plogis(b_Intercept), 
                    #dim green -> dim UV = UV effect + UVdim - dim effect
                    gl_uvl = plogis(b_Intercept + b_colouru +
                                      `b_brightnl.colouru`) - 
                              plogis(b_Intercept + b_brightnl)
                  )
                }

empirical.p = function(x, tails = 2){ifelse(test = median(x)>0,
                                            yes = mean(x<0)*tails, 
                                            no = mean(x>0)*tails)
}

Investigate effect of sun elevation

### Maximal formula with all random effects ---------------------
#set up model formula with indiv effects on light type
frm_elemod_maxRE = bf(mean_vector~ cos(sun_el_rad) + # accuracy is affected by projection distortion at high elevations following a cosine law
                            (1 |ID), # each individual is more or less oriented
              phi ~ cos(sun_el_rad) + # accuracy is affected by projection distortion at high elevations following a cosine law
                      (1 |ID), # some individuals vary more in accuracy than others
              family = brms::Beta()) 

#suggest prior values
pr_mu_Intercept = list(dist = 'normal',
             mu = 0,
             sd = 1)#deconstrain to beat divergences?
pr_phi_Intercept = list(dist = 'normal',
             mu = 1,
             sd = 1)
pr_mu_b = list(dist = 'normal',
             mu = 0,
             sd = 1)#deconstrain to beat divergences?
pr_phi_b = list(dist = 'normal',
             mu = 0,
             sd = 1)
pr_mu_sd_Intercept = list(dist = 'student_t',
             df = 3,
             mu = 0,
             sd = 0.1)#constrain to beat divergences?
pr_phi_sd_Intercept = list(dist = 'student_t',
                 df = 3,
                 mu = 0,
                 sd = 0.1)#constrain to beat divergences?
pr_mu_sd = list(dist = 'student_t',
             df = 3,
             mu = 0,
             sd = 0.1)#constrain to beat divergences?
pr_phi_sd = list(dist = 'student_t',
                 df = 3,
                 mu = 0,
                 sd = 0.1)#constrain to beat divergences?

### Assign priors --------------------------------------------------------

#set priors on:
# - all coefficients to a normal(0,1) = 95% probability of values 0.120.87
# - all grouping paramters to a student_t(df = 3, mu = 0, sigma = 2.5) = values < 5.88
# - all other parameters (?) to a normal(0,10)= 95% probability of values 01 +- 1e-7

pr_expression = expression({
  prior = sapply(class, 
                 switch,
                 Intercept = with(pr_mu_Intercept,
                          {paste0(dist,'(',mu,',',sd,')')}),
                 #the general prior for coefficients (should centre on 0)
                 b = with(pr_mu_b,
                          {paste0(dist,'(',mu,',',sd,')')}),
                 #the general prior for standard deviations (should be long-tailed)
                 sd =  with(pr_mu_sd,
                           {paste0(dist,'(',df,',',mu,',',sd,')')}),
                 cor = 'lkj(1)', # The only supported prior for correlation matrices is the 'lkj' prior
                 'normal(0,1)' # with this many params need more informative priors
      )
  #special priors
    #mu sd intercept
  prior[dpar %in% '' & class %in% 'sd' & coef %in% ''] =  
    with(pr_mu_sd_Intercept,
                          {paste0(dist,'(',df,',',mu,',',sd,')')})
  #phi b
  prior[dpar %in% 'phi' & class %in% 'b'] =  
    with(pr_phi_b,
                          {paste0(dist,'(',mu,',',sd,')')})
  #phi intercept
  prior[dpar %in% 'phi' & class %in% 'b' & coef %in% ''] =  
    with(pr_phi_Intercept,
                          {paste0(dist,'(',mu,',',sd,')')})
  #phi sd
  prior[dpar %in% 'phi' & class %in% 'sd'] =  
    with(pr_phi_sd,
                          {paste0(dist,'(',df,',',mu,',',sd,')')})  
  #phi sd intercept
  prior[dpar %in% 'phi' & class %in% 'sd' & coef %in% ''] =  
    with(pr_phi_sd_Intercept,
                          {paste0(dist,'(',df,',',mu,',',sd,')')})
}
)

#model with all random effects
priors_elemod_mxRE = within(get_prior(formula = frm_elemod_maxRE, 
                                    data = mean_vectors_full), 
                          expr = eval(pr_expression))
print(priors_elemod_mxRE)#all parameters are accounted for

Comparison with Edrich et al. (1979)

How does this compare with previous experiments in which a light spot (2.3) was presented through bandpass filters and ND filters to produce different intensities? In that data, there was a clear sigmoidal relationship between intensity and accuracy (mean vector length). They mention that the particular relationship with light intensity was variable, but that the relative relationships remained constant, so we may also observe the same relationship but shifted.

Unfortunately, the scatter of the dance directions as a function of light intensity proved to be unstable over long periods of time; the absolute values changed from day to day. However, these changes were such that curves for adjacent wavelengths were shifted in parallel - the relative sensitivities remained constant. Edrich et al.(1979), p154

Plot raw data from Edrich et al. (1979) Fig. 2

This is best modelled with a nonlinear (psychometric model) following the beta distribution (for variables bounded between zero and one).

Reorganise data

ed = within(ed,
            {
              logit_accuracy = qlogis(accuracy)
              log10_intensity = log10(intensity)
              colour = sapply(paste(wavelength),
                              FUN = switch,
                              `354` = 'UV',
                              `429` = 'blue',
                              `535` = '0green',
                              NA)
            }
            )

Fit psychometric curves

For each light stimulus, fit a sigmoid curve bounded between baseline accuracy (shared across stimuli) and maximum accuracy (1 - lapses). Inflection point and 80%-rise-region width vary between stimuli, maximising posterior probability for a beta distribution in (0,1). To do this, we first define a nonlinear formula in brms.

#set up model fit
formula_beta = bf(
  formula = accuracy ~ 
    inv_logit(LogitBase) + (1 - inv_logit(LogitLapse) - inv_logit(LogitBase) ) *#curve region
    inv_logit( 4.39*(log10_intensity - Inflex) / exp(LogWidth) ) , #inflection-width curve
  # for each of these parameters, we can set up a separate formula 
  # that describes how to predict them from the data 
  #Base rate of correct choices: "
  LogitBase ~ 1, #Base rate of correct choices: "~ 1" gives the instruction "estimate the mean across all data"
  #Lapse rate on a log(odds) scale:
  LogitLapse ~ colour, #this is similar to the formula in our LMM example
  #inflection point of the initial curve:
  Inflex ~ colour, #N.B. this is similar to the intercept, so it does not include effects of stimulus level
  #log 80% width of the curve:
  LogWidth ~ colour, #N.B. this is similar to the slope, so all of its effects depend on stimulus level
  family = Beta(link = "identity", link_phi = 'log'),
  nl = TRUE)#the joint distribution for these parameters is undefined, and therefore the parameters themselves are "nonlinear"

Since this is a nonlinear model (there are terms both inside and outside the logistic transform) it is important to establish prior distributions for all parameters. These ensure that parameter estimates explore credible ranges during fitting. The baseline is expected to be around \(r = 0.27\), while the maximum accuracy should be around \(r = 0.95\), and their estimates should not converge (that would flatten the curve, or reverse its direction). The inflection points are expected around \(10^{11}\) photons cm\(^{-2}\) s\(^{-1}\), with a rise-region width of \(10^{3}\) photons cm\(^{-2}\) s\(^{-1}\). All colour effects may vary by a few orders of magnitude.

#set up priors
prior_beta = get_prior(formula = formula_beta,
                     data = ed)
#set the prior distribution
prior_beta = within(prior_beta, 
                  { prior[
                    class %in% 'b' & #just the fixed effects
                      nlpar %in% 'LogitBase' &
                      coef %in% 'Intercept' 
                  ] = 'normal(-1,1)' #a normal distribution centred on plogis(-1) = 0.27
                  })
#this prior is automatically bounded between 0 and 1, 
#Lapse rate priors ---------------------------------------------------
prior_beta = within(prior_beta, 
                  { prior[
                    class %in% 'b' & #just the fixed effects
                      nlpar %in% 'LogitLapse' &
                      coef %in% 'Intercept' 
                  ] = 'normal(-3,2)' #a normal distribution centred on -3
                  })

#for all other fixed effects on lapse rate, we'll suggest values around 0 (no effect)
prior_beta = within(prior_beta, 
                  { prior[
                    class %in% 'b' & #just the fixed effects
                      nlpar %in% 'LogitLapse' &
                      coef %in% 'colourblue' 
                  ] = 'normal(0,2)' #a normal distribution:mean 0, sd 3
                  })
prior_beta = within(prior_beta, 
                  { prior[
                    class %in% 'b' & #just the fixed effects
                      nlpar %in% 'LogitLapse' &
                      coef %in% 'colourUV' 
                  ] = 'normal(0,2)' #a normal distribution:mean 0, sd 3
                  })

#Inflection point priors ---------------------------------------------
prior_beta = within(prior_beta, 
                  { prior[
                    class %in% 'b' & #just the fixed effects
                      nlpar %in% 'Inflex' &
                      coef %in% 'Intercept'
                  ] = 'normal(11,2)' #a normal distribution:mean 11, sd 2
                  })
#for all coefficients, we'll suggest values around 0 (no effect)
prior_beta = within(prior_beta, 
                  { prior[
                    class %in% 'b' & #just the fixed effects
                      nlpar %in% 'Inflex' &
                      coef %in% 'colourblue' 
                  ] = 'normal(0,2)' #a normal distribution:mean 0, sd 2
                  })

prior_beta = within(prior_beta, 
                  { prior[
                    class %in% 'b' & #just the fixed effects
                      nlpar %in% 'Inflex' &
                      coef %in% 'colourUV' 
                  ] = 'normal(0,2)' #a normal distribution:mean 0, sd 2
                  })

#Rise region width priors --------------------------------------------
prior_beta = within(prior_beta, 
                  { prior[
                    class %in% 'b' & #just the fixed effects
                      nlpar %in% 'LogWidth' &
                      coef %in% 'Intercept' 
                  ] = 'normal(1,2)' #a normal distribution:mean 1, sd 3
                  })
#for all coefficients, we'll suggest values around 0 (no effect)
prior_beta = within(prior_beta, 
                  { prior[
                    class %in% 'b' & #just the fixed effects
                      nlpar %in% 'LogWidth' &
                      coef %in% 'colourblue'
                  ] = 'normal(0,2)' #a normal distribution:mean 0, sd 3
                  })
prior_beta = within(prior_beta, 
                  { prior[
                    class %in% 'b' & #just the fixed effects
                      nlpar %in% 'LogWidth' &
                      coef %in% 'colourUV'
                  ] = 'normal(0,2)' #a normal distribution:mean 0, sd 3
                  })

Fit a psychometric model to the data using the nonlinear formula and specified prior distributions. 4000 iterations on 4 chains takes less than one minute.

#takes less than 1 minute
#parameters for the brms runs
wup = 2000
sam = 2000
refr = 0
system.time(
  {
    beta_fit = brm( formula = formula_beta, # using our nonlinear formula
                     data = ed, # our data
                     prior = prior_beta, # our priors 
                     iter = wup+sam, # long run for 4000 iterations
                     chains = 4, # 4 chains in parallel
                     cores = 4, # on 4 CPUs
                     refresh = refr,
                     silent = 0, # don't echo chain progress
                     control = list(adapt_delta = 0.95), #finer sampling
                     backend = 'cmdstanr') # use cmdstanr (other compilers broken)
  }
)

Extract the model predictions by summarising parameter estimates from the sampling phases of all chains. To identify specific combinations of parameter values, use the conditional_effects function, which organises all simultaneous estimates into a data frame.

# #N.B. for plotting we will need to also define "inv_logit" in our the R environment
inv_logit = inv_logit_scaled # this can be found in brms, but with an additional specifier

#summary of parameter estimates
full_sm_beta = summary(beta_fit,
                  robust = TRUE)#use the median estimate

#Extract fixed effects estimates
full_fix_beta = full_sm_beta$fixed
#extract rownames
full_fix_rn_beta = rownames(full_fix_beta)

# stimulus levels to add to the dataset to be able to measure this effect.
full_estimates_beta = full_fix_beta$Estimate
names(full_estimates_beta) = full_fix_rn_beta

# to predict all effects, we can use the 'posterior_epred' method
#by default 100 predictions per continuous variable (but fewer for their interactions)
#This takes <2 seconds
system.time(
  {
    full_cond_beta =brms::conditional_effects(beta_fit, 
                                         method = 'posterior_epred', # posterior epred not working
                                         cores =  parallel::detectCores()-1,
                                         effects = c('log10_intensity:colour'),
                                         plot = FALSE
    )
  }
)
##    user  system elapsed 
##    4.14    0.25    4.58
#extract predictions
pred_data_beta = full_cond_beta$`log10_intensity:colour`

#Green light curve
g_curve = 
with(data.frame(t(full_estimates_beta)),
     {
       list(Base = plogis(LogitBase_Intercept),
            Maxima = 1- plogis(LogitLapse_Intercept), 
            Inflection = Inflex_Intercept,  
            Width = exp(LogWidth_Intercept)  
       )
     }
)

#UV light curve
u_curve = 
with(data.frame(t(full_estimates_beta)),
     {
       list(Base = plogis(LogitBase_Intercept),
            Maxima = 1- plogis(LogitLapse_Intercept + LogitLapse_colourUV), 
            Inflection = Inflex_Intercept + Inflex_colourUV,  
            Width = exp(LogWidth_Intercept + LogWidth_colourUV)  
       )
     }
)

It would be difficult to explain the orientation accuracy for the high intensity (\(4*10^{14}\)) UV stimulus from the accuracy curve for Edrichs UV data, but it would fit well with the maximum accuracy observed for green light. In Edrichs study, the green light was interpreted as the sun (dances at correct angle between sun and feeder), whereas the UV light was interpreted as a patch of sky near the anti-sun. In Khns data the stimuli were larger (assuming \(10\) across) than Edrichs (\(2.3\)), which may have resulted in them being perceived as dimmer (left shift in this graph).

Sun compass orientation

Since most dances were at least somewhat oriented (\(r>0.5\)) we can assume that the mean angles of these dances typically align with an intended dance direction. If most dances are for the same geographic location, we should observe dances as the same fixed angle to the stimulus, interpreted either as the sun or the anti-sun.

sun_diff_gh = sapply(X = u_id,
                    FUN = SunDiff,
                    dt = mean_vectors,
                    cl = 'g',
                    br = 'h')
sun_diff_gl = sapply(X = u_id,

For the bright stimuli the dances generally indicate South, but with a very wide range. (or possibly clusters to the South-West and South-East). For the dim stimuli there is less of a clear pattern, particularly for UV dim.

When restricting to only the balanced cases, the pattern becomes clearer. For the most oriented dances to the bright UV stimulus there are two clusters to the South-West and South-East. These are likely also present for the bright green stimulus. The dim green stimulus appears to align somewhat with the bright stimuli. The dim UV stimulus shows no apparent patten, though a slight southwards bias.

Compare Sun-Spot & Phototaxis Hypotheses

It is likely that a plurality of dancers had visited locations in the Marburg Botanic Gardens, perhaps in the centre of the main growing area (504803.3N 84824.1E). The hive is at 504822.7N 84840.8E. That would give the following bearing:

## 218.6614 200.9496 173.1410
garden_bearing_rad = rad(as.numeric(garden_bearing[2]))
#TODO save and load models instead of running them each time
load_model = TRUE
# Custom family --------------------------------------------------------
#In the "unwrap" family, all variables 
unwrap_von_mises = custom_family(
  "unwrap_von_mises", dpars = c("mu", "kappa"),
  links = c('identity',#brms cannot accept custom link functions, do via nl instead
            "softplus"), 
  lb = c(-pi, 0),
  ub = c(pi, NA),
  type = "real"
)

## Stan variables 


### Functions 

stan_unwrap_fun = stanvar(scode = "
  real unwrap_von_mises_lpdf(real y, real mu, real kappa) {
    return von_mises_lpdf(y | mod_circular(mu), kappa);
  }
  real unwrap_von_mises_rng(real mu, real kappa) {
    return von_mises_rng( mod_circular(mu) , kappa);
  }
  real unwrap_von_mises_vect_lpdf(vector y, real mu, real kappa) {
    real tmp = 0;
    for(i in 1:size(y))
    {
    tmp = tmp + unwrap_von_mises_lpdf(y[i] | mu, kappa);
    }
      return tmp;
  }
",
                          block = 'functions') + 
  stanvar(scode = "
  real mod_circular(real y) {
    return fmod(y + pi(), 2*pi()) - pi();
  }

  real inv_mod_circular(real y) {
    return mod_circular(y);
  }
",
          block = 'functions') 

### Parameters

#concentration of random effects on fixed effect on mean angle
kappamu_param = stanvar(scode = "
real kappamu;
                           ",
                            block = "parameters") + 
  stanvar(scode = "
real kappa_mu = log1p_exp(kappamu);
          ", 
          block = 'genquant')


stanvars_unwrap = stan_unwrap_fun + kappamu_param

#subset to just gh data
cd_gh = subset(cd,
               subset = brightn %in% 'h' & 
                         colour %in% 'g' & 
                         !is.na(sun_az_rad) # for fair comparison only include cases where the sun azimuth is known
               )

dt_photo = within(cd_gh,
            {
              BR = brightn
              CL = colour
              DT = date
              RN = run
              sunangle = angle + sun_az_rad
            }
)

#TODO oops I forgot this is a huge amount of data, I'll try the full set later

# dt_photo = subset(dt_photo,
#                   subset = ID %in% full_ids)

dt_sun = within(dt_photo,
                {bgangle = sunangle - garden_bearing_rad}
                )


# Model formulae
#model assuming mean direction at 0, with individual biases
formula_photo = bf(
  formula = angle ~ mu,
            nlf(mu ~ fmu + zmu), 
            fmu ~ 0, # fixed effects intercept == 0
            zmu ~ 0 + ID,
            kappa ~ 1 + (1|ID),
  family = unwrap_von_mises,#mod mu, kappa via the softplus
  nl = TRUE)#to accept user-defined extra parameters (zmu) we need to treat the formula as nonlinear

#model allowing any angle
formula_nophoto = bf(
  formula = angle ~ mu,
            nlf(mu ~ fmu + zmu), 
            fmu ~ 1, # fixed effects intercept estimated
            zmu ~ 0 + ID,
            kappa ~ 1 + (1|ID),
  family = unwrap_von_mises,#mod mu, kappa via the softplus
  nl = TRUE)#to accept user-defined extra parameters (zmu) we need to treat the formula as nonlinear

formula_sunspot = bf(
  formula = bgangle ~ mu,
            nlf(mu ~ fmu + zmu), 
            fmu ~ 0, # fixed effects intercept estimated
            zmu ~ 0 + ID,
            kappa ~ 1 + (1|ID),
  family = unwrap_von_mises,#mod mu, kappa via the softplus
  nl = TRUE)#to accept user-defined extra parameters (zmu) we need to treat the formula as nonlinear

formula_nosunspot = bf(
  formula = bgangle ~ mu,
            nlf(mu ~ fmu + zmu), 
            fmu ~ 1, # fixed effects intercept estimated
            zmu ~ 0 + ID,
            kappa ~ 1 + (1|ID),
  family = unwrap_von_mises,#mod mu, kappa via the softplus
  nl = TRUE)#to accept user-defined extra parameters (zmu) we need to treat the formula as nonlinear

# Priors
#priors for mu
pr_photo = 
  set_prior(paste("target +=", 
                  'unwrap_von_mises_vect_lpdf(b_zmu | 0, log1p_exp(kappamu))',
                  '+ normal_lpdf(b_zmu | 0, 2*pi())'# additional prior to keep estimates from walking around the circle
  ),
  check = FALSE) +
  set_prior("target += normal_lpdf(kappamu | 1.0, 3.0)", #prior to lower values, indiv differences should be large
            check = FALSE) +
    prior(normal(3.0,3.0), class = Intercept, dpar = 'kappa') + # bias to oriented
  prior(student_t(3, 0, 3.0), class = sd, dpar = 'kappa')  # weak bias no differences

#for models with a mean we also need an extra parameter
pr_nophoto = pr_photo +
  prior(normal(0,2*pi()), class = b,  nlpar = 'fmu', coef = 'Intercept')

#parameters for the brms runs
wup = 1000
sam = 1000
refr = 0
siln = 0

#these are pretty slow! About 7 minutes in total
if(load_model)
{ load(file = '2Results/phototaxis_modlist.RData')
}else
  {
  cglm_photo = brm(formula = formula_photo,
                  data = dt_photo,
                  prior = pr_photo,
                  stanvars = stanvars_unwrap,
                  warmup = wup,#may be necessary 
                  iter = wup+sam, #doesn't take a lot of runs
                  chains = 4, # 4 chains in parallel
                  cores = 4, # on 4 CPUs
                  # control = list(adapt_delta = 0.90),
                 refresh = refr, # echo chain progress every n iterations
                 silent = siln, # echo some Stan messages
                  save_pars = save_pars(all = TRUE), # <--- Crucial for moment matching
                 backend = 'cmdstanr')
  
  cglm_nophoto = brm(formula = formula_nophoto,
                  data = dt_photo,
                  prior = pr_nophoto,
                  stanvars = stanvars_unwrap,
                  warmup = wup,#may be necessary 
                  iter = wup+sam, #doesn't take a lot of runs
                  chains = 4, # 4 chains in parallel
                  cores = 4, # on 4 CPUs
                  # control = list(adapt_delta = 0.90),
                 refresh = refr, # echo chain progress every n iterations
                 silent = siln, # echo some Stan messages
                  save_pars = save_pars(all = TRUE), # <--- Crucial for moment matching
                 backend = 'cmdstanr')
  
  cglm_sunspot = brm(formula = formula_sunspot,
                  data = dt_sun,
                  prior = pr_photo,#different response, same predictors
                  stanvars = stanvars_unwrap,
                  warmup = wup,#may be necessary 
                  iter = wup+sam, #doesn't take a lot of runs
                  chains = 4, # 4 chains in parallel
                  cores = 4, # on 4 CPUs
                  # control = list(adapt_delta = 0.90),
                 refresh = refr, # echo chain progress every n iterations
                 silent = siln, # echo some Stan messages
                  save_pars = save_pars(all = TRUE), # <--- Crucial for moment matching
                 backend = 'cmdstanr')  
  
  cglm_nosunspot = brm(formula = formula_nosunspot,
                  data = dt_sun,
                  prior = pr_nophoto,#different response, same predictors
                  stanvars = stanvars_unwrap,
                  warmup = wup,#may be necessary 
                  iter = wup+sam, #doesn't take a lot of runs
                  chains = 4, # 4 chains in parallel
                  cores = 4, # on 4 CPUs
                  control = list(adapt_delta = 0.90),
                 refresh = refr, # echo chain progress every n iterations
                 silent = siln, # echo some Stan messages
                  save_pars = save_pars(all = TRUE), # <--- Crucial for moment matching
                 backend = 'cmdstanr')
#combine into a single list
modlist = list(phototaxis = cglm_photo,
            no_phototaxis = cglm_nophoto,
            sunspot = cglm_sunspot,
            no_sunspot = cglm_nosunspot)
  }
#summarise
suppressWarnings({ #for circular models rhats may be smaller than they appear
sm_modlist = lapply(X = modlist,
       FUN = summary)
})
Sm_only = function(x,
                   type = 'fixed',
                   var = 'kappa_Intercept')
{
  x[[type]][var,]
}

#average kappa
print(lapply(X = sm_modlist, Sm_only), digits = 3 )

#TODO add to functions

PostROPE = function(id, rope, drs, mu = 'b_fmu_Intercept')
{
  mu = if(!is.na(mu)){with(drs, get(mu))}else{0}
  dr_id = with(drs,
               {
               mod_circular(
                 mu +
                  get(paste0('b_zmu_ID', id)
                            )
               )
               }
              )
  #centre both
  circ_rope = circular(rope, template = 'none')
  circ_dr = circular(dr_id, template = 'none')
  mean_rope = mean.circular(circ_rope)
  rope_ctr = as.numeric(mod_circular(circ_rope - mean_rope))
  dr_ctr = as.numeric(mod_circular(dr_id - mean_rope))
  postp = mean( rope_ctr[1] < dr_id &
                dr_id  < rope_ctr[2])
  return(postp)
}

photo_id = unique(dt_photo$ID)

#width of sector
rope_width = abs(mod_circular(rad(diff(garden_bearing[-2])))) # 35
rope_photo = c(-1,1)*rope_width/2
rope_sunspot = sort( mod_circular(rad(garden_bearing[-2] - garden_bearing[2])) )

postl_nophoto  = sapply(X = photo_id,
       FUN = PostROPE,
       rope = rope_photo,

       )

       FUN = PostROPE,
       rope = rope_photo,

       FUN = PostROPE,

       drs = dr_modlist$no_sunspot
       )

       FUN = PostROPE,

       drs = dr_modlist$sunspot,

Mean dance angles relative to the stimulus (full conditions)

Since dances do not point to a specific geographic location, it is possible that they advertise a variety of directions relative to the sun, or are not menotactic but phototactic or uniformly oriented. We can identify phototactic orientation from the angle relative to the stimulus.

par(mfrow = c(2,2), mar = c(0,0,0,0))
PCfun(angles = subset(mean_vectors_full, 
                      subset = colour %in% 'g' & brightn %in% 'h')$mu,
      col = 'green',
      shrink = 1.5,
      title = 'Green Bright')
PCfun(angles = subset(mean_vectors_full, 
                      subset = colour %in% 'g' & brightn %in% 'l')$mu,
      col = 'darkgreen',
      shrink = 1.5,
      title = 'Green Dim')
PCfun(angles = subset(mean_vectors_full, 
                      subset = colour %in% 'u' & brightn %in% 'h')$mu,
      col = 'magenta',
      shrink = 1.5,
      title = 'UV Bright')
PCfun(angles = subset(mean_vectors_full, 
                      subset = colour %in% 'u' & brightn %in% 'l')$mu,
      col = 'purple',
      shrink = 1.5,
      title = 'UV Dim')

While there are some dances towards or near to the stimulus for most conditions, there is a wide spread, suggesting a factor other than phototaxis sets dance directions. N.B. for the dim stimuli where the widest spread is observed, the dances are also less accurate, which may increase variation in mean dance angle.

cd_sd_full = aggregate(circular(mu, units = 'degrees')~colour*brightn,
                  FUN = sd.circular,
                  data = mean_vectors_full)
cd_rho_full = aggregate(circular(mu, units = 'degrees')~colour*brightn,
                  FUN = rho.circular,
                  data = mean_vectors_full)
names(cd_sd_full)[3] = 'circular_sd'
names(cd_rho_full)[3] = 'rho'
cd_desc_full = merge(cd_sd_full, cd_rho_full)
cd_desc_full = within(cd_desc_full, 
                 {sd_degrees = deg(circular_sd)})
print(cd_desc_full,digits = 2)

Change in mean dance angle between stimuli

Change arcs

To determine whether these dances interpret the stimuli as the sun, anti-sun or something else, we would need to check the differences in dance angle between the conditions. It is also worth considering any differences in accuracy between dances to each condition, since this would influence the variation in angular change. These can be visualised as arcs.

Estimate turn effects

Find fit maximum likelihood turn distributions

For each change distribution, find the maximum likelihood von Mises distribution. For the UV high to UV low change, this will be a bimodal distribution.

#collect all heading differences
pair_diffs_lst = lapply(X = list(#bright vs dim green
                                green_hl = mu_diff_gl, 
                                #bright vs dim UV
                                uv_hl = mu_diff_uhl,
                                #bright green vs bright uv 
                                uvg_h = mu_diff_uh,
                                #dim green vs bright UV
                                 uvg_l = mu_diff_gul ), 
                        FUN = unlist) 
#Provide appropriate data format
angle_unit = 'degrees' 
angle_rot = 'clock'
#make sure they are in circular format
pair_diffs_lst = lapply(X = pair_diffs_lst,
                        FUN = circular,
                        units = angle_unit,
                        rotation = angle_rot)

Fit the maximum likelihood distribution for no difference between pairs, differences between pairs, and differences between pairs with two means. If angles shift in one direction between trials, the difference distribution should have significantly higher likelihood. If angles shift in two directions between pairs, then the two means distribution should be the best fit.

#TODO neaten up!
#Distribution for same means
ml_same_lst = lapply(X = pair_diffs_lst,
                     mle.vonmises,
                     bias = TRUE,
                     mu = circular(x = 0,
                                   units = angle_unit,
                                   rotation = angle_rot)
)
#Distribution for different means
ml_diff_lst = lapply(X = pair_diffs_lst,
                     mle.vonmises,
                     bias = TRUE)
#Distribution for multiple different means
mod_diff_lst = lapply(X = pair_diffs_lst,
                      FUN = circ_mle,#converts circular format data to radians
                      niter = 1e4)#some stochastic variability for green stim

                      niter = 1e4)#some stochastic variability for green stim

                      FUN = MD_extract) )

                      FUN = MD_extract) )

# Calculate likelihood 
#calculate all in list
all_ll = mapply(FUN = LLcalc,
                ml = c(ml_same_lst, ml_diff_lst), #apply to both sets of ML estimates
                angles = pair_diffs_lst, #repeat datasets
                au = angle_unit, #important, use the same frame of reference as the original
                ar = angle_rot)

#inspect resulting parameters
mod_diff_results = do.call(rbind, c(ml_same_lst, ml_diff_lst))

                          rep(x = c( 'same', 'diff'),

                           times = 2)

#reorder for easy comparison
rspar = rspar[c(rbind(1:4, 1:4+4)),]#put the different directly after the same
rspar[,3:4] = NA
rspar = cbind(rspar, weight1 = 1.0)
colnames(rspar) = colnames(bim_diff_par)[c(1:4, 6:5)]
all_res = rbind(data.frame(rspar),
                data.frame(bim_diff_par) )
all_res = apply(all_res, MARGIN = 2, FUN = unlist)
rn_res = rownames(all_res)#NB in R4.5 need to make a copy of rownames
rn_res[9:12] = paste('multi', rownames(bim_diff_par))
rownames(all_res) = rn_res #

                 {

As expected, the bimodal models fitted by circ_mle have the highest likelihood, followed by the models for differences and then the models for no difference. The difference models require at 1 more parameter, so should increase likelihood by >1 order of magnitude to be appropriate. The bimodal model require 2 more parameters, so should increase likelihood by >2 log units.

Estimate confidence intervals

For each mean, simulate a distribution of mean estimates

#estimate CI for unimodal von Mises models
mle_CI = with(data.frame(mod_diff_results), 
              {
              mapply(FUN = CI_vM, 
                     angles = pair_diffs_lst, 
                     m1 = mu, 
                     k1 = kappa, 
                     w1 = 1,
                     alternative = 'two.sided',#not a hypothesis test (symmetrical)
                     n = 1e4)#takes 30s for 10 000 simulations
                }
              )
#reorder for comparison like the original models
mle_CI =  t(mle_CI)[c(rbind(1:4, 1:4+4)),]
rownames(mle_CI) = rownames(rspar)
colnames(mle_CI) = c('lower','median','upper')

#estimate CI for unimodal and bimodal von Mises models
mod_CI = with(data.frame(mod_diff_par), 
              {
              mapply(FUN = CI_vM, 
                     angles = pair_diffs_lst, 
                     m1 = mu1, 
                     k1 = kappa1, 
                     m2 = mu2, 
                     k2 = kappa2, 
                     w1 = weight1,
                     alternative = 'two.sided',#not a hypothesis test (symmetrical)
                     # SIMPLIFY = FALSE,
                     n = 1e4)#takes 15 for 10 000 simulations
                }
              )
#estimate CI for unimodal and bimodal von Mises models
bim_CI = with(data.frame(bim_diff_par), 
              {
              mapply(FUN = CI_vM, 
                     angles = pair_diffs_lst, 
                     m1 = mu1, 
                     k1 = kappa1, 
                     m2 = mu2, 
                     k2 = kappa2, 
                     w1 = weight1,
                     SIMPLIFY = FALSE,
                     alternative = 'two.sided',#not a hypothesis test (symmetrical)
                     n = 1e4)#takes 15 for 10 000 simulations
                }
              )
#collapse to printable table
mod_CI_tb = Table_vCI(mod_CI)
bim_CI_tb = Table_vCI(bim_CI)
print(mle_CI, digits = 3)

We see here that while the confidence interval for the difference distribution between the two green conditions and the two bright conditions nearly overlap with 0 (and the 0 distribution CI overlap with the mean difference), for differences between green lights and dim UV there is a bimodal distribution with CI that do not overlap with 0. Here we see that the confidence interval for the difference between the green conditions overlaps with 0, and the one for the two bright conditions almost does (the one sided CI does, but looks odd due it its asymmetry). To confirm whether these models better explain the data than the null hypothesis of the same mean for each condition (no difference), we can perform a likelihood-ratio test.

Likelihood ratio tests

For each condition, compare the models for same mean, different mean and multiple means. First perform all tests separately, then collect them together and finally adjust for multiple tests before reporting.

mod_details= lapply(X = names(pair_diffs_lst),
                     FUN = CollectDetails,
                     ll = all_res,
                     bimod = TRUE)
names(mod_details) = names(pair_diffs_lst)


#save details
save(x = mod_details, 
          file = '2Results/MLEdetails_paired_diffs.RData')

#set up tests for hypotheses
lr_tests = c('pairs_diff_zero', #is the turn different from zero?
             'pairs_multi_diff', #is the turn in one or two directions?
             'pairs_multi_zero' #are the two directions different from zero?
             )#multiple tests

#Perform collect likelihood ratio tests for each hypothesis
all_lr_results_lst = lapply(X =mod_details,
                           FUN = LR_calc_lst,
                           tst = lr_tests)
all_lr_results = do.call(what = rbind,
                          args = all_lr_results_lst
                          )
all_lr_results = within(data.frame(all_lr_results),
                        {
                            comparison = c( sapply(X = names(mod_details), 
                            FUN = rep,
                            times = length(lr_tests)
                            ) )
                            test = rep(lr_tests, 
                                      times = length(names(mod_details))
                            ) 
                        }
                      )
# lapply(
#        all_lr_results_lst,
#        FUN = print,
#        digits = 3
#        )

#add labels to interpret each test according to p value and sign of comparison
all_lr_results = within(all_lr_results,
                     {
                       result = mapply(tst = lr_tests,
                                       d0 = unlist(dev0),
                                       d1 = unlist(dev1),
                                       pa = p_adjusted,
                                       FUN = H1label
                       )
                     }
)
print_lr_results = all_lr_results
print_lr_results = within(print_lr_results,
                          {
                            rm(dev0,dev1, p)
                          test = sub(sub(sub(test, 
                                     pattern = '_', 
                                     replacement = ' '),
                                     pattern = '_', 
                                     replacement = ' '),
                                     pattern = 'pairs ',
                                     replacement = '')
                          mu1 = round(all_res$mu1, 1)
                          }
                          )
print_lr_results = within(print_lr_results,
                           {mu2 = round(all_res$mu2, 1)}
                          )
rownames(print_lr_results) = with(print_lr_results, paste(comparison, test))#better to keep them for the html
#Round numeric columns
# print_lr_results = apply(print_lr_results, MARGIN = 2, FUN = unlist)
num_col = sapply(X = print_lr_results, 
                 FUN = is.numeric)
print_lr_results[,num_col] = apply(X = print_lr_results[,num_col],
                                   MARGIN = 2, 
                                   FUN = round, 
                                   digits = 3)
#Print the results
print(print_lr_results[,-6],
      digits = 3)

These tests confirm, that there is no significant difference between the two green conditions, a marginally-significant 13 left turn between the bright conditions, and significant bimodal differences between the two UV conditions and the two dim conditions, driven by left and right turns for the dim UV condition.

                      phi~1),
                   data = dt_ang_uhl,

##   Links: mu = logit; phi = log 
## Formula: betaresp ~ 1 
##          phi ~ 1
##    Data: dt_ang_uhl (Number of observations: 17) 
##   Draws: 4 chains, each with iter = 2000; warmup = 1000; thin = 1;
##          total post-warmup draws = 4000
## 
## Regression Coefficients:
##               Estimate Est.Error l-95% CI u-95% CI Rhat Bulk_ESS Tail_ESS
## Intercept        -0.10      0.19    -0.47     0.27 1.00     2347     2189
## phi_Intercept     1.79      0.34     1.07     2.42 1.00     2900     2415
## 
## Draws were sampled using sample(hmc). For each parameter, Bulk_ESS
## and Tail_ESS are effective sample size measures, and Rhat is the potential
## scale reduction factor on split chains (at convergence, Rhat = 1).
loo_beta_uhl = loo(beta_ang_uhl)
loo_beta_uhl_null = loo(beta_ang_uhl_null)
loo_compare(loo_beta_uhl, loo_beta_uhl_null)
##                   elpd_diff se_diff
## beta_ang_uhl_null  0.0       0.0   
## beta_ang_uhl      -1.0       0.6
#the distribution is concave (phi>2) in 99.9% of draws
mean(
  exp(
    as_draws_df(beta_ang_uhl_null,
                dpar = 'Intercept_phi')$Intercept_phi
    )<2) *100
## [1] 0.1
#estimate mean angular difference
emm_ang_uhl = emmeans(beta_ang_uhl,
                      specs = '1')
print(
  summary(emm_ang_uhl,
              type = 'response')[2:4]*180,
  digits = 1)
##   response lower.HPD upper.HPD
